# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: eric-reissner
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] The once Celtic settlement was equipped with several *thermae* in the course of colonization by Roman pioneers settling at the warm Aachen thermal springs around the 1st century.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] After the withdrawal of the Roman troops, the vicus *Aquae Granni* was Frankized around the 5th century, by which it came under Merovingian and later Carolingian rule.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] With the completion of the Carolingian Palace of Aachen at the transition to the 9th century, Aachen was constituted as the main royal residence of the Frankish Empire ruled by Charlemagne.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] Because of that, the city is sometimes called the "cradle of Europe".
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] After the Treaty of Verdun, the city was within the borders of Middle Francia, until it became part of East Francia after the Treaty of Meerssen (870).
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] It subsequently was part of the Holy Roman Empire and was granted city rights in 1166 by Emperor Frederick Barbarossa, becoming an imperial city.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] It served as the coronation site where 31 Holy Roman Emperors were crowned Kings of the Germans from 936 to 1531, until Frankfurt became the preferred place of coronation.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] One of Germany's leading institutes of higher education in technology, the RWTH Aachen University *(Rheinisch-Westfälisch Technische Hochschule Aachen)*, is located in the city.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] Its university hospital Uniklinikum Aachen is Europe's largest single-building hospital.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] Aachen's industries include science, engineering and information technology.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] In 2009, Aachen was ranked eighth among cities in Germany for innovation.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] Aachen is located at the northern foothills of the High Fens and the Eifel Mountains.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] It sits on the Wurm River, a tributary of the Rur, and together with Mönchengladbach, it is the only larger German city in the drainage basin of the Meuse.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] The regional dialect spoken in the city is a Central Franconian, Ripuarian variant with strong Limburgish influences from the dialects in the neighbouring Netherlands.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] As a Rhenish city, Aachen is one of the main centres of carnival celebrations in Germany, along with Cologne and Mainz.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] The culinary specialty for which the city is best known is Aachener Printen, a type of gingerbread.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] The name *Aachen* is a modern descendant, like southern German *Ach(e)*, German: *Aach*, meaning "river" or "stream", from Old High German *ahha*, meaning "water" or "stream", which directly translates (and etymologically corresponds) to Latin *Aquae*, referring to the springs.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] The location has been inhabited by humans since the Neolithic era, about 5,000 years ago, attracted to its warm mineral springs.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] Latin *Aquae* figures in Aachen's Roman name *Aquae granni*, which meant "waters of Grannus", referring to the Celtic god of healing who was worshipped at the springs.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] This word became *Åxhe* in Walloon and *Aix* in French, and subsequently *Aix-la-Chapelle* to distinguish it from Aix-en-Provence, after Charlemagne had his palatine chapel built there in the late 8th century and then made the city his empire's capital.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] Flint quarries on the Lousberg, Schneeberg, and Königshügel, first used during Neolithic times (3000–2500 BC), attest to the long occupation of the site of Aachen, as do recent finds under the modern city's *Elisengarten* pointing to a former settlement from the same period.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] Bronze Age (around 1600 BC) settlement is evidenced by the remains of barrows (burial mounds) found, for example, on the Klausberg.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] During the Iron Age, the area was settled by Celtic peoples who were perhaps drawn by the marshy Aachen basin's hot sulphur springs where they worshipped Grannus, god of light and healing.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] Proofs of a Celts settlements on Aachens territories at the beginning of the Gallic War do not exist at the moment.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] The 25-hectare Roman spa resort town of Aquae Granni was, according to legend, founded by Grenus, under Hadrian, around 124 AD.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] Grenus refers to the Celtic god, and it seems it was the Roman 6th Legion at the start of the 1st century AD that first channelled the hot springs into a spa at Büchel, adding at the end of the same century the *Münstertherme* spa, two water pipelines, and a probable sanctuary dedicated to Grannus.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] A kind of forum, surrounded by colonnades, connected the two spa complexes.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] There was an extensive residential area.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] The Romans built bathhouses near Burtscheid.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] A temple precinct called *Vernenum* was built near the modern Kornelimünster/Walheim.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] Today, remains have been found of three bathhouses, including two fountains in the *Elisenbrunnen* and the Burtscheid bathhouse.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] Roman civil administration in Aachen eventually broke down as the baths and other public buildings (along with most of the villae rusticae of the surrounding countryside) were destroyed around AD 375 at the start of the migration period.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] The last Roman coin finds are from the time of Emperor Gratian (AD 375–383).
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] Rome withdrew its troops from the area, but the town remained populated.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] By 470, the town came to be ruled by the Ripuarian Franks and subordinated to their capital, Cologne.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] During the Roman period, Aachen was the site of a flourishing Jewish community.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] Pepin the Short had a castle residence built in the town, due to the proximity of the hot springs and also for strategic reasons as it is located between the Rhineland and northern France.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] In the year of his coronation as king of the Franks, 768, Charlemagne came to spend Christmas at Aachen for the first time.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] He remained there in a mansion which he may have extended, although there is no source attesting to any significant building activity at Aachen in his time, apart from the building of the Palatine Chapel (since 1930, cathedral) and the Palace.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] Charlemagne spent most winters in Aachen between 792 and his death in 814.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] Aachen became the focus of his court and the political centre of his empire.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] During the Carolingian empire, a Jewish community lived near the royal palace.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] In Jewish texts, the city of Aachen was called *Aish* or *Ash* (אש).
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] In 797, Isaac, a Jewish merchant, accompanied two ambassadors of Charlemagne to the court of Harun al-Rashid.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] He returned to Aachen in July 802, bearing an elephant called Abul-Abbas as a gift for the emperor.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] By the terms of the Treaty of Verdun 834, Aachen became part of Middle Francia, governed by emperor Lothair.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] He was succeeded by Lothair II as king of Lotharingia by the terms of the Treaty of Prüm.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] By the Treaty of Meerssen 870, Aachen came to East Francia.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] Within East Francia, later the Holy Roman Empire until 1166, Aachen was part of the Duchy of Lower Lotharingia.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] In 936, Otto I was crowned king of East Francia in the collegiate church built by Charlemagne.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] During the reign of Otto II, the nobles revolted and the West Franks under Lothair raided Aachen in 978.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] Aachen was attacked again by Odo of Champagne, who attacked the imperial palace while Conrad II was absent.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] Odo relinquished it and was killed afterwards.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] The palace and town of Aachen had fortifying walls built by order of Emperor Frederick Barbarossa between 1172 and 1176.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] Over the next 500 years, most kings of Germany who ruled the Holy Roman Empire were crowned in Aachen.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] The original audience hall built by Charlemagne was torn down and replaced by the current city hall in 1330.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] During the 13th century, many Jews converted to Christianity, as shown in the records of the Aachen Minster (today's Cathedral).
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] In 1486, the Jews of Aachen offered gifts to Maximilian I during his coronation ceremony.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] The last king to be crowned here was Ferdinand I in 1531.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] During the Middle Ages, Aachen remained a city of regional importance, due to its proximity to Flanders; it achieved a modest position in the trade in woollen cloths, favoured by imperial privilege.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] The city remained a free imperial city, subject to the emperor only, but was politically far too weak to influence the policies of any of its neighbours.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] The only dominion it had was over Burtscheid, a neighbouring territory ruled by a Benedictine abbess, which was forced to accept that all of its traffic must pass through the "Aachener Reich".
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] As an imperial city, Aachen held certain political privileges that allowed it to remain independent of the troubles of Europe for many years.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] It remained a direct vassal of the Holy Roman Empire throughout most of the Middle Ages.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] It was also the site of many important church councils, including the Council of 837 and the Council of 1166, a council convened by the antipope Paschal III.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] Parts of Aachen belonged to Imperial Abbey of Burtscheid, Reichsabtei Kornelimünster, Duchy of Juelich and the Duchy of Limburg.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] Aachen was an important site for the production of historical manuscripts.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] Under Charlemagne's purview, both the Ada Gospels and the Coronation Gospels may have been produced in Aachen.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] In addition, quantities of the other texts in the court library were also produced locally.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] During the reign of Louis the Pious (814–840), substantial quantities of ancient texts were produced at Aachen, including legal manuscripts such as the leges scriptorium group, patristic texts including the five manuscripts of the Bamberg Pliny Group.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] Finally, under Lothair I (840–855), texts of outstanding quality were still being produced.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] This however marked the end of the period of manuscript production at Aachen.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] In 1598, following the invasion of Spanish troops from the Netherlands, Rudolf deposed all Protestant office holders in Aachen and went as far as expelling them from the city.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] From the early 16th century, Aachen started to lose its power and influence.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] First the coronations of emperors were moved from Aachen to Frankfurt.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] 1614 Aachen became theatre of the Siege of Aachen (1614) within the War of the Jülich Succession.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] Although religious changes were forced several times in Aachen and Protestant communities were banned, hardly any fighting took place during the Thirty Years' War.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] The religious wars had been followed by the great fire of 1656.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] After the destruction of most of the city in 1656, the rebuilding was mostly in the Baroque style.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] The decline of Aachen culminated in 1794, when the French, led by General Charles Dumouriez, occupied Aachen..
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] The area of Aachen had been scene of battles within the Flanders Campaign in autumn 1794: Battle of Ourthe, Battle of Aldenhoven, Siege of Maastricht.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] In 1542, the Dutch humanist and physician Francis Fabricius published his study of the health benefits of the hot springs in Aachen.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] By the middle of the 17th century, the city had developed a considerable reputation as a spa, although this was in part because Aachen was then – and remained well into the 19th and early 20th century – a place of high-level prostitution.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] Traces of this hidden agenda of the city's history are found in the 18th-century guidebooks to Aachen as well as to the other spas.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] The main indication for visiting patients, ironically, was syphilis; only by the end of the 19th century had rheumatism become the most important object of cures at Aachen and Burtscheid.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] Aachen was chosen as the site of several important congresses and peace treaties: the first congress of Aachen (often referred to as the Congress of Aix-la-Chapelle in English) on 2 May 1668, leading to the First Treaty of Aachen in the same year which ended the War of Devolution.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] The second congress ended with the second treaty in 1748, ending the War of the Austrian Succession.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] In 1789, there was a constitutional crisis in the Aachen government, and in 1794 Aachen lost its status as a free imperial city.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] In 1629, the Aachen Jewish community was expelled from the city.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] In 1667, six Jews were allowed to return.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] Most of the Aachen Jewish community settled in Burtscheid.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] As recently as the late 18th century the Abbess of Burtscheid was still prevented from building a road linking her territory to the neighbouring estates of the duke of Jülich; the city of Aachen deployed its handful of soldiers to chase away road-diggers.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] On 9 February 1801, the Peace of Lunéville removed the ownership of Aachen and the entire "left bank" of the Rhine from Germany (the Holy Roman Empire) and granted it to France.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] In 1815, control of the town was passed to the Kingdom of Prussia through an agreement reached by the Congress of Vienna.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] The third congress took place in 1818, to decide the fate of occupied Napoleonic France.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] The current territory of Aachen belonged entirely to the Arrondissement d'Aix-la-Chapelle.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] In 1815, after the Second Treaty of Paris, finishing the Napoleonic Wars, the Kingdom of Prussia took over within the new German Confederation.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] The city was one of its most socially and politically backward centres until the end of the 19th century.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] The Kingdom of Prussia created the "Regierungsbezirk Aachen" (governmental district) and integrated it into the Prussian province Grand Duchy of the Lower Rhine, from 1822 the Rhine Province.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] Starting in 1838, the railway from Cologne to Belgium passed through Aachen.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] By "Gesetz betreffend die Vereinigung der Stadtgemeinde Burtscheid mit der Stadtgemeinde Aachen vom 29.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] März 1897 nebst Vertrag" Aachen and Burtscheid merged 1897.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] The city suffered extreme overcrowding and deplorable sanitary conditions until 1875, when the medieval fortifications were abandoned as a limit to building and new, better housing was built in the east of the city, where sanitary drainage was easiest.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] In December 1880, the Aachen tramway network was opened, and in 1895 it was electrified.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] In the 19th century and up to the 1930s, the city was important in the production of railway locomotives and carriages, iron, pins, needles, buttons, tobacco, woollen goods, and silk goods.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] Aachen was enlarged 1 April 1906 by "Gesetz betreffend die Vereinigung der Gemeinde Forst mit der Stadtgemeinde Aachen vom 31.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] März 1906 nebst Vertrag" by incorporation of Forst.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] The Belgium Campaign within World War I started in Aachen.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] After World War I, Aachen was occupied by the Entente until 1930, along with the rest of German territory west of the Rhine.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] Aachen was one of the locations involved in the Rhenish Republic.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] On 21 October 1923, an armed mob took over the city hall.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] Similar actions took place in Mönchengladbach, Duisburg, and Krefeld.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] During the interwar period, Aachen was assigned some areas of the former district of Eupen.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] Also the Western Campaign of World War II started nearby Aachen with the Battle of Maastricht.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] Aachen was heavily damaged during World War II.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] Blood mentioned more than 120 air strikes on Aachen between 1940 an 1944.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] According to Jörg Friedrich in *The Fire* (2002), two Allied air raids on 11 April and 24 May 1944 "radically destroyed" the city.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] The first killed 1,525, including 212 children, and bombed six hospitals.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] During the second, 442 aircraft hit two railway stations, killed 207, and left 15,000 homeless.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] The raids destroyed Aachen-Eilendorf and Aachen-Burtscheid.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] In autumn 1944 Aachen and its surroundings were reached by the Western Allied Siegfried Line campaign.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] The city and its fortified surroundings were besieged from 12 September to 21 October 1944 by the US 1st Infantry Division with the 3rd Armored Division assisting from the south.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] Around 13 October the US 2nd Armored Division, coming from the north, and got as close as Würselen, while the 30th Infantry Division completed the encirclement of Aachen on 16 October 1944.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] With reinforcements from the US 28th Infantry Division the battle continued involving direct assaults through the heavily defended city, which forced the German garrison to surrender on 21 October 1944.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] Aachen was the first German city to be captured by the Western Allies, and its residents welcomed the soldiers as liberators.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] What remained of the city was destroyed—in some areas completely—during the fighting, mostly by American artillery fire and demolitions carried out by the Waffen-SS defenders.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] Damaged buildings included medieval churches and the Rathaus (city hall), although Aachen Cathedral was largely unscathed.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] 4,000 inhabitants remained in the city; the rest had followed evacuation orders.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] Its first Allied-appointed mayor, Franz Oppenhoff, was assassinated by an SS commando unit.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] On 16 May 1815, the Jewish community of the city offered an homage in its synagogue to the Prussian king, Friedrich Wilhelm III.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] In 1862, a large synagogue was built, later called the Old Synagogue.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] On *Kristallnacht* in 1938, the synagogue was destroyed.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] By the onset of World War II in 1939, many Jews had emigrated or were arrested, and only 782 remained in the city.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] At the end of the war in 1945, only 62 Jews lived in the city.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] As of 2003, 1,434 Jews were again living in Aachen.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] Subsequent the German surrender finishing the Battle of Aachen 21 October 1944, the Supreme Headquarters Allied Expeditionary Force acted as military government.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] Aachen within the northern part of Rhine Province became part of British occupation zone in Germany.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] Aachen also belonged to the British zone under Belgian control.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] 46, British Military Government created the "Land Nordrhein/Westfalen", including the "Regierungsbezirk Aachen", 23 August 1946.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] 23 May 1949 Aachen became part of the Federal Republic of Germany.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] With the Aachen Law of 1971, Aachen was merged with Kornelimünster, Brand, Walheim, Laurensberg, Richterich, Haaren, Eilendorf.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] After the abolition of the Aachen governmental district, August 1972, Aachen became part of the Cologne governmental district.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] Aachen is located in the middle of the Meuse–Rhine Euroregion, close to the border tripoint of Germany, the Netherlands, and Belgium.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] The town of Vaals in the Netherlands lies nearby at about 6 km (4 mi) from Aachen's city centre, while the Dutch city of Heerlen and Eupen, the capital of the German-speaking Community of Belgium, are both located about 20 km (12 mi) from Aachen city centre.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] Aachen lies near the head of the open valley of the Wurm (which today flows through the city in canalised form), part of the larger basin of the Meuse, and about 30 km (19 mi) north of the High Fens, which form the northern edge of the Eifel uplands of the Rhenish Massif.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] The maximum dimensions of the city's territory are 21.6 km (13+3⁄8 mi) from north to south, and 17.2 km (10+3⁄4 mi) from east to west.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] The highest point in Aachen, located in the far southeast of the city, lies at an elevation of 410 m (1,350 ft) above sea level.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] The lowest point, in the north, and on the border with the Netherlands, is at 125 m (410 ft).
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] As the westernmost city in Germany (and close to the Low Countries), Aachen and the surrounding area belongs to a temperate climate zone (Cfb), with humid weather, mild winters, and warm summers.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] Because of its location north of the Eifel and the High Fens and its subsequent prevailing westerly weather patterns, rainfall in Aachen (on average 805 mm/year) is comparatively higher than, for example, in Bonn (with 669 mm/year).
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] Another factor in the local weather forces of Aachen is the occurrence of Foehn winds on the southerly air currents, which results from the city's geographic location on the northern edge of the Eifel.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] Because the city is surrounded by hills, it suffers from inversion-related smog.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] Some areas of the city have become urban heat islands as a result of poor heat exchange, both because of the area's natural geography and from human activity.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] The city's numerous cold air corridors, which are slated to remain as free as possible from new construction, therefore play an important role in the urban climate of Aachen.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] The January average is 3.0 °C (37 °F), while the July average is 18.5 °C (65 °F).
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] Precipitation is almost evenly spread throughout the year.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] In the 1991–2020 period, the record latest freeze (at 2 m above ground) of spring occurred on 28 April and the record first fall freeze on 13 October.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] The geology of Aachen is very structurally heterogeneous.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] The oldest occurring rocks in the area surrounding the city originate from the Devonian period and include carboniferous sandstone, greywacke, claystone and limestone.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] These formations are part of the Rhenish Massif, north of the High Fens.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] In the Pennsylvanian subperiod of the Carboniferous geological period, these rock layers were narrowed and folded as a result of the Variscan orogeny.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] After this event, and over the course of the following 200 million years, this area has been continuously flattened.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] During the Cretaceous period, the ocean penetrated the continent from the direction of the North Sea up to the mountainous area near Aachen, bringing with it clay, sand, and chalk deposits.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] While the clay (which was the basis for a major pottery industry in nearby Raeren) is mostly found in the lower areas of Aachen, the hills of the Aachen Forest and the Lousberg were formed from upper Cretaceous sand and chalk deposits.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] More recent sedimentation is mainly located in the north and east of Aachen and was formed through Tertiary and Quaternary river and wind activities.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] Along the major thrust fault of the Variscan orogeny, there are over 30 thermal springs in Aachen and Burtscheid.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] At the end of 2009, the foreign-born residents of Aachen made up 13.6 percent of the total population.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] A significant portion of foreign residents are students at the RWTH Aachen University.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] Aachen is at the western end of the Benrath line that divides High German to the south from the rest of the West Germanic speech area to the north.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] Aachen's local dialect is called *Öcher Platt* and belongs to Ripuarian.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] The city is divided into seven administrative districts, or boroughs, each with its own district council, district leader, and district authority.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] The councils are elected locally by those who live within the district, and these districts are further subdivided into smaller sections for statistical purposes, with each sub-district named by a two-digit number.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] The current mayor of Aachen is Michael Ziemons of the CDU, who was elected in 2025.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] The Aachen city council governs the city alongside the mayor.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] Aachen Cathedral was erected on the orders of Charlemagne.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] Construction began *c.* AD 796, and it was, on completion *c.* 798, the largest cathedral north of the Alps.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] It was modelled after the Basilica of San Vitale, in Ravenna, Italy, and was built by Odo of Metz.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] Charlemagne also desired for the chapel to compete with the Lateran Palace, both in quality and authority.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] It was originally built in the Carolingian style, including marble covered walls, and mosaic inlay on the dome.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] On his death, Charlemagne's remains were interred in the cathedral and can be seen there to this day.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] The cathedral was extended several times in later ages, turning it into a curious and unique mixture of building styles.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] The throne and gallery portion date from the Ottonian, with portions of the original opus sectile floor still visible.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] The 13th century saw gables being added to the roof, and after the fire of 1656, the dome was rebuilt.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] Finally, a choir was added around the start of the 15th century.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] After Frederick Barbarossa canonised Charlemagne in 1165 the chapel became a destination for pilgrims.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] For 600 years, from 936 to 1531, Aachen Cathedral was the church of coronation for 30 German kings and 12 queens.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] The church built by Charlemagne is still the main attraction of the city.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] In addition to holding the remains of its founder, it became the burial place of his successor Otto III.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] In the upper chamber of the gallery, Charlemagne's marble throne is housed.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] Aachen Cathedral has been designated as a UNESCO World Heritage Site.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] Most of the marble and columns used in the construction of the cathedral were brought from Rome and Ravenna, including the sarcophagus in which Charlemagne was eventually laid to rest.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] A bronze bear from Gaul was placed inside, along with an equestrian statue from Ravenna, believed to be Theodric, in contrast to a wolf and a statue of Marcus Aurelius in the Capitoline.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] Bronze pieces such as the doors and railings, some of which have survived to present day, were cast in a local foundry.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] Finally, there is uncertainty surrounding the bronze pine cone in the chapel, and where it was created.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] Wherever it was made, it was also a parallel to a piece in Rome, this in Old St.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] Aachen Cathedral Treasury has housed, throughout its history, a collection of liturgical objects.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] The origin of this church treasure is in dispute as some say Charlemagne himself endowed his chapel with the original collection, while the rest were collected over time.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] Others say all of the objects were collected over time, from such places as Jerusalem and Constantinople.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] The location of this treasury has moved over time and was unknown until the 15th century when it was located in the Matthiaskapelle (St.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] Matthew's Chapel) until 1873, when it was moved to the Karlskapelle (Charles' Chapel).
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] From there it was moved to the Hungarian Chapel in 1881 and in 1931 to its present location next to the Allerseelenkapelle (Poor Souls' Chapel).
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] Only six of the original Carolingian objects have remained, and of those only three are left in Aachen: the Aachen Gospels, a diptych of Christ, and an early Byzantine silk.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] The Coronation Gospels and a reliquary burse of St.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] Stephen were moved to Vienna in 1798 and the Talisman of Charlemagne was given as a gift in 1804 to Josephine Bonaparte and subsequently to Rheims Cathedral.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] 210 documented pieces have been added to the treasury since its inception, typically to receive in return legitimisation of linkage to the heritage of Charlemagne.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] The Lothar Cross, the Gospels of Otto III and multiple additional Byzantine silks were donated by Otto III.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] Part of the Pala d'Oro and a covering for the Aachen Gospels were made of gold donated by Henry II.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] Frederick Barbarossa donated the candelabrum that adorns the dome and also once "crowned" the Shrine of Charlemagne, which was placed underneath in 1215.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] Charles IV donated a pair of reliquaries.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] Louis XI gave, in 1475, the crown of Margaret of York, and, in 1481, another arm reliquary of Charlemagne.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] Maximilian I and Charles V both gave numerous works of art by Hans von Reutlingen.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] Continuing the tradition, objects continued to be donated until the present, each indicative of the period of its gifting, with the last documented gift being a chalice from 1960 made by Ewald Mataré.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] The Aachen Rathaus, (English: Aachen City Hall or Aachen Town Hall) dated from 1330, lies between two central squares, the *Markt* (marketplace) and the *Katschhof* (between city hall and cathedral).
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] The coronation hall is on the first floor of the building.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] Inside one can find five frescoes by the Aachen artist Alfred Rethel which show legendary scenes from the life of Charlemagne, as well as Charlemagne's signature.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] Also, precious replicas of the Imperial Regalia are kept here.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] Since 2009, the city hall has been a station on the *Route Charlemagne*, a tour programme by which historical sights of Aachen are presented to visitors.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] At the city hall, a museum exhibition explains the history and art of the building and gives a sense of the historical coronation banquets that took place there.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] A portrait of Napoleon from 1807 by Louis-André-Gabriel Bouchet and one of his wife Joséphine from 1805 by Robert Lefèvre are viewable as part of the tour.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] As before, the city hall is the seat of the mayor of Aachen and of the city council, and annually the Charlemagne Prize is awarded there.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] The *Grashaus*, a late medieval house at the *Fischmarkt*, is one of the oldest non-religious buildings in central Aachen.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] It hosted the city archive, and before that, the Grashaus was the city hall until the present building took over this function.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] The *Elisenbrunnen* is one of the most famous sights of Aachen.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] It is a neo-classical hall covering one of the city's famous fountains.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] It is just a minute away from the cathedral.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] Just a few steps in a south-easterly direction lies the 19th-century theatre.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] Also of note are two remaining city gates, the *Ponttor* (Pont gate), 800 metres (1⁄2 mile) northwest of the cathedral, and the *Marschiertor* (marching gate), close to the central railway station.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] There are also a few parts of both medieval city walls left, most of them integrated into more recent buildings, but some others still visible.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] There are even five towers left, some of which are used for housing.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] Michael's Church, Aachen was built as a church of the Aachen Jesuit Collegium in 1628.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] It is attributed to the Rhine mannerism, and a sample of a local Renaissance architecture.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] The rich façade remained unfinished until 1891, when the architect Peter Friedrich Peters added to it.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] The church is a Greek Orthodox church today, but the building is used also for concerts because of its good acoustics.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] The synagogue in Aachen, which was destroyed on the Night of Broken Glass (Kristallnacht), 9 November 1938, was reinaugurated on 18 May 1995.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] One of the contributors to the reconstructions of the synagogue was Jürgen Linden, the Lord Mayor of Aachen from 1989 to 2009.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] There are numerous other notable churches and monasteries, a few remarkable 17th- and 18th-century buildings in the particular Baroque style typical of the region, a synagogue, a collection of statues and monuments, park areas, cemeteries, among others.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] Among the museums in the town are the Suermondt-Ludwig Museum, which has a fine sculpture collection and the Aachen Museum of the International Press, which is dedicated to newspapers from the 16th century to the present.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] The area's industrial history is reflected in dozens of 19th- and early 20th-century manufacturing sites in the city.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] Aachen is the administrative centre for the coal-mining industries in neighbouring places to the northeast.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] Products manufactured in Aachen include electrical goods, fine woolen textiles, foodstuffs (chocolate and candy), glass, machinery, rubber products, furniture, metal products.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] Also in and around Aachen chemicals, plastics, cosmetics, and needles and pins are produced.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] Though once a major player in Aachen's economy, today glassware and textile production make up only 10% of total manufacturing jobs in the city.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] There have been a number of spin-offs from the university's IT technology department.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] In June 2010, Achim Kampker, together with Günther Schuh, founded a small company to develop electric powered light utility vehicles; in August 2014, it was renamed StreetScooter GmbH.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] This started as a privately organised research initiative at the RWTH Aachen University, before becoming the independent company in Aachen.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] Kampker was also the founder and chairman of the European Network for Affordable and Sustainable Electromobility.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] In May 2014, the company announced that the city of Aachen, the city council Aachen and the savings bank Aachen had ordered electric vehicles from the company.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] In late 2014, approximately 70 employees were manufacturing 200 vehicles annually in the premises of the Waggonfabrik Talbot, the former Talbot/Bombardier plant in Aachen.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] In December 2014 DHL Group purchased the StreetScooter company from Günther, operating it as a wholly owned subsidiary.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] In 2015, Günther founded a new electric vehicle company, e.GO Mobile, which started producing the e.GO Life electric passenger car and other vehicles in April 2019.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] By April 2016, StreetScooter announced that it would produce 2000 of its electric vans, branded the Work, in Aachen by the end of the year, and would be scaling up to manufacture approximately 10,000 Works annually, starting in 2017, also in Aachen.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p01] At the time, this target would make it the largest electric light utility vehicle manufacturer in Europe, surpassing Renault's smaller Kangoo Z.E.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p02] RWTH Aachen University, established as Polytechnicum in 1870, is one of Germany's Universities of Excellence with strong emphasis on technological research, especially for electrical and mechanical engineering, computer sciences, physics, and chemistry.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p02] The university clinic attached to the RWTH, the Klinikum Aachen, is the biggest single-building hospital in Europe.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p02] Over time, a host of software and computer industries have developed around the university.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p02] It also maintains a botanical garden (the Botanischer Garten Aachen).
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p02] FH Aachen, Aachen University of Applied Sciences (AcUAS) was founded in 1971.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p02] The AcUAS offers a classic engineering education in professions such as mechatronics, construction engineering, mechanical engineering or electrical engineering.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p02] German and international students are educated in more than 20 international or foreign-oriented programmes and can acquire German as well as international degrees (Bachelor/Master) or *Doppelabschlüsse* (double degrees).
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p02] Foreign students account for more than 21% of the student body.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p02] The Katholische Hochschule Nordrhein-Westfalen – Abteilung Aachen (Catholic University of Applied Sciences Northrhine-Westphalia – Aachen department) offers its some 750 students a variety of degree programmes: social work, childhood education, nursing, and co-operative management.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p02] It also has the only programme of study in Germany especially designed for mothers.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p02] The Hochschule für Musik und Tanz Köln (Cologne University of Music) is one of the world's foremost performing arts schools and one of the largest music institutions for higher education in Europe with one of its three campuses in Aachen.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p02] The Aachen campus substantially contributes to the Opera/Musical Theatre master's programme by collaborating with the Theater Aachen and the recently established musical theatre chair through the Rheinische Opernakademie.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p02] The German Army's technical school *(Ausbildungszentrum Technik Landsysteme)* is located in Aachen.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p02] The annual CHIO (short for the French term *Concours Hippique International Officiel*) is the biggest equestrian meeting of the world and among horsemen is considered to be as prestigious for equitation as the tournament of Wimbledon for tennis.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p02] Aachen hosted the 2006 FEI World Equestrian Games.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p02] The local football team Alemannia Aachen had a short run in Germany's first division, after its promotion in 2006.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p02] However, the team could not sustain its status and is now back in the third division.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p02] The stadium "Tivoli", opened in 1928, served as the venue for the team's home games and was well known for its incomparable atmosphere throughout the whole of the second division.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p02] Before the old stadium's demolition in 2011, it was used by amateurs, whilst the Bundesliga Club held its games in the new stadium "Neuer Tivoli" – meaning New Tivoli—a couple of metres down the road.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p02] The building work for the stadium which has a capacity of 32,960, began in May 2008 and was completed by the beginning of 2009.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p02] The Ladies in Black women's volleyball team (part of the "PTSV Aachen" sports club since 2013) has played in the first German volleyball league (DVL) since 2008.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p02] In June 2022, the local basketball club BG Aachen e.V. was promoted to the 1st regional league.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p02] Aachen's railway station, the Hauptbahnhof (Central Station), was constructed in 1841 for the Cologne–Aachen railway line.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p02] In 1905, it was moved closer to the city centre.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p02] It serves main lines to Cologne, Mönchengladbach and Liège as well as branch lines to Heerlen, Alsdorf, Stolberg and Eschweiler.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p02] ICE high speed trains from Brussels via Cologne to Frankfurt am Main and Eurostar trains from Paris to Cologne also stop at Aachen Central Station.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p02] Four RE lines and two RB lines connect Aachen with the Ruhrgebiet, Mönchengladbach, Spa (Belgium), Düsseldorf and the Siegerland.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p02] The *Euregiobahn*, a regional railway system, reaches several minor cities in the Aachen region.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p02] There are four smaller stations in Aachen: *Aachen West*, *Aachen Schanz*, *Aachen-Rothe Erde* and *Eilendorf*.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p02] Aachen West has gained in importance with the expansion of RWTH Aachen University.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p02] There are two stations for intercity bus services in Aachen: Aachen West station, in the north-west of the city, and Aachen Wilmersdorfer Straße, in the north-east.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p02] The first horse tram line in Aachen opened in December 1880.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p02] After electrification in 1895, it attained a maximum length of 213.5 kilometres (132+5⁄8 miles) in 1915, thus becoming the fourth-longest tram network in Germany.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p02] Many tram lines extended to the surrounding towns of Herzogenrath, Stolberg, Alsdorf as well as the Belgian and Dutch communes of Vaals, Kelmis (then *Altenberg*) and Eupen.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p02] The Aachen tram system was linked with the Belgian national interurban tram system.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p02] Like many tram systems in Western Europe, the Aachen tram suffered from poorly maintained infrastructure and was so deemed unnecessary and disrupting for car drivers by local politics.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p02] On 28 September 1974, the last line 15 (Vaals–Brand) operated for one last day and was then replaced by buses.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p02] A proposal to reinstate a tram/light rail system under the name *Campusbahn* was dropped after a referendum.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p02] Today, the ASEAG (*Aachener Straßenbahn und Energieversorgungs-AG*, literally "Aachen Tram and Power Supply Company") operates a 1,240.8-kilometre-long (771 mi) bus network with 68 bus routes.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p02] Because of the location at the border, many bus routes extend to Belgium and the Netherlands.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p02] Lines 14 to Eupen, Belgium and 44 to Heerlen, Netherlands are jointly operated with Transport en Commun and Veolia Transport Nederland, respectively.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p02] ASEAG is one of the main participants in the Aachener Verkehrsverbund (AVV), a tariff association in the region.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p02] Along with ASEAG, city bus routes of Aachen are served by private contractors such as Sadar, Taeter, Schlömer, or DB Regio Bus.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p02] Line 350, which runs from Maastricht, also enters Aachen.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p02] Aachen is connected to the Autobahn A4 (west-east), A44 (north-south) and A544 (a smaller motorway from the A4 to the *Europaplatz* near the city centre).
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p02] There are plans to eliminate traffic jams at the Aachen road interchange.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p02] Maastricht Aachen Airport (IATA: **MST**, ICAO: **EHBK**) is the main airport of Aachen and Maastricht.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p02] It is located around 15 nautical miles (28 kilometres; 17 miles) northwest of Aachen.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p02] There is a shuttle-service between Aachen and the airport.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p02] However, the airport only offers limited European destinations.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p02] The nearest major international airports are Cologne Bonn Airport, located 88 km (55 mi) east and Düsseldorf Airport, located 97.1 km (60 mi) northeast of Aachen.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p02] Recreational aviation is served by the (formerly military) Aachen Merzbrück Airfield.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p02] Since 1950, a committee of Aachen citizens annually awards the Charlemagne Prize (German: *Karlspreis*) to personalities of outstanding service to the unification of Europe.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p02] It is traditionally awarded on Ascension Day at the City Hall.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p02] In 2016, the Charlemagne Award was awarded to Pope Francis.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p02] In 2004, Pope John Paul II's efforts to unite Europe were honoured with an "Extraordinary Charlemagne Medal", which was awarded for the only time ever.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p02] Aix is the destination in Robert Browning's poem "How They Brought the Good News from Ghent to Aix", which was published in *Dramatic Romances and Lyrics*, 1845.
[src:eric-reissner/aachen-p02] The poem is a first-person narrative told, in breathless galloping meter, by one of three riders; an urgent midnight errand to deliver "the news which alone could save Aix from her fate".
[src:eric-reissner/aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator] Cohen graduated from Thomas Jefferson High School in San Antonio, Texas.
[src:eric-reissner/aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator] He received a Bachelor of Science degree from Texas A&M University in 1952, a Master of Science degree from Stevens Institute of Technology in 1958, and an honorary doctorate from Stevens in 1982.
[src:eric-reissner/aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator] Cohen joined NASA in 1962 and served in key leadership roles critical to the success of the flights and lunar landings of the Apollo Program.
[src:eric-reissner/aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator] From 1969 to 1972, Cohen was the manager for the Apollo Command and Service Modules.
[src:eric-reissner/aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator] He oversaw the design, development, production and test flights of the Space Shuttles as manager of NASA's Space Shuttle Orbiter Project Office from 1972 to 1982.
[src:eric-reissner/aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator] After serving as Director of Engineering at Johnson for several years, he was named director of the center in 1986, serving in that post until 1993.
[src:eric-reissner/aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator] After his retirement from NASA, Cohen taught mechanical engineering design at Texas A&M University.
[src:eric-reissner/aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator] In 2000, he was appointed Professor Emeritus, and in 2010, he was awarded an honorary Doctor of Letters.
[src:eric-reissner/aerospace-engineering] "Aeronautical engineering" was the original term for the field.
[src:eric-reissner/aerospace-engineering] As flight technology advanced to include vehicles operating in outer space, the broader term "aerospace engineering" has come into use.
[src:eric-reissner/aerospace-engineering] Aerospace engineering, particularly the astronautics branch, is often colloquially referred to as "rocket science".
[src:eric-reissner/aerospace-engineering] Flight vehicles are subjected to demanding conditions such as those caused by changes in atmospheric pressure and temperature, with structural loads applied upon vehicle components.
[src:eric-reissner/aerospace-engineering] Consequently, they are usually the products of various technological and engineering disciplines including aerodynamics, air propulsion, avionics, materials science, structural analysis and manufacturing.
[src:eric-reissner/aerospace-engineering] The interaction between these technologies is known as aerospace engineering.
[src:eric-reissner/aerospace-engineering] Because of the complexity and number of disciplines involved, aerospace engineering is carried out by teams of engineers, each having their own specialized area of expertise.
[src:eric-reissner/aerospace-engineering] The origin of aerospace engineering can be traced back to the aviation pioneers around the late 19th to early 20th centuries, although the work of Sir George Cayley dates from the last decade of the 18th to the mid-19th century.
[src:eric-reissner/aerospace-engineering] One of the most important people in the history of aeronautics and a pioneer in aeronautical engineering, Cayley is credited as the first person to separate the forces of lift and drag, which affect any atmospheric flight vehicle.
[src:eric-reissner/aerospace-engineering] Early knowledge of aeronautical engineering was largely empirical, with some concepts and skills imported from other branches of engineering.
[src:eric-reissner/aerospace-engineering] Some key elements, like fluid dynamics, were understood by 18th-century scientists.
[src:eric-reissner/aerospace-engineering] In December 1903, the Wright Brothers performed the first sustained, controlled flight of a powered, heavier-than-air aircraft, lasting 12 seconds.
[src:eric-reissner/aerospace-engineering] The 1910s saw the development of aeronautical engineering through the design of World War I military aircraft.
[src:eric-reissner/aerospace-engineering] In 1914, Robert Goddard was granted two U.S. patents for rockets using solid fuel, liquid fuel, multiple propellant charges, and multi-stage designs.
[src:eric-reissner/aerospace-engineering] This would set the stage for future applications in multi-stage propulsion systems for outer space.
[src:eric-reissner/aerospace-engineering] Congress established the first aeronautical research administration, known as the National Advisory Committee for Aeronautics, or NACA.
[src:eric-reissner/aerospace-engineering] It was the first government-sponsored organization to support aviation research.
[src:eric-reissner/aerospace-engineering] Though intended as an advisory board upon inception, the Langley Aeronautical Laboratory became its first sponsored research and testing facility in 1920.
[src:eric-reissner/aerospace-engineering] The organization would later be redefined as NASA, the National Aeronautics and Space Administration.
[src:eric-reissner/aerospace-engineering] Between World Wars I and II, great leaps were made in the field, accelerated by the advent of mainstream civil aviation.
[src:eric-reissner/aerospace-engineering] Notable airplanes of this era include the Curtiss JN 4, Farman F.60 Goliath, and Fokker Trimotor.
[src:eric-reissner/aerospace-engineering] Notable military airplanes of this period include the Mitsubishi A6M Zero, Supermarine Spitfire and Messerschmitt Bf 109 from Japan, United Kingdom, and Germany respectively.
[src:eric-reissner/aerospace-engineering] A significant development came with the first operational Jet engine-powered airplane, the Messerschmitt Me 262 which entered service in 1944 towards the end of the Second World War.
[src:eric-reissner/aerospace-engineering] The first definition of aerospace engineering appeared in February 1958, considering the Earth's atmosphere and outer space as a single realm, thereby encompassing both aircraft (*aero*) and spacecraft (*space*) under the newly coined term *aerospace*.
[src:eric-reissner/aerospace-engineering] In response to the USSR launching the first satellite, Sputnik, into space on October 4, 1957, U.S. aerospace engineers launched the first American satellite on January 31, 1958.
[src:eric-reissner/aerospace-engineering] The National Aeronautics and Space Administration was founded in 1958 after the Sputnik crisis.
[src:eric-reissner/aerospace-engineering] In 1969, Apollo 11, the first human space mission to land on the Moon, took place.
[src:eric-reissner/aerospace-engineering] It saw three astronauts enter orbit around the Moon, with two, Neil Armstrong and Buzz Aldrin, visiting the lunar surface.
[src:eric-reissner/aerospace-engineering] The third astronaut, Michael Collins, stayed in orbit to rendezvous with Armstrong and Aldrin after their visit.
[src:eric-reissner/aerospace-engineering] An important innovation came on January 30, 1970, when the Boeing 747 made its first commercial flight from New York to London.
[src:eric-reissner/aerospace-engineering] This aircraft made history and became known as the "Jumbo Jet" or "Queen of the Skies" due to its ability to hold up to 480 passengers.
[src:eric-reissner/aerospace-engineering] Another significant development came in 1976, with the development of the first passenger supersonic aircraft, the Concorde.
[src:eric-reissner/aerospace-engineering] The development of this aircraft was agreed upon by the French and British on November 29, 1962.
[src:eric-reissner/aerospace-engineering] On December 21, 1988, the Antonov An-225 *Mriya* cargo aircraft commenced its first flight.
[src:eric-reissner/aerospace-engineering] It holds the records for the world's heaviest aircraft, heaviest airlifted cargo, and longest airlifted cargo of any aircraft in operational service.
[src:eric-reissner/aerospace-engineering] On October 25, 2007, the Airbus A380 made its maiden commercial flight from Singapore to Sydney, Australia.
[src:eric-reissner/aerospace-engineering] This aircraft was the first passenger plane to surpass the Boeing 747 in terms of passenger capacity, with a maximum of 853.
[src:eric-reissner/aerospace-engineering] Though development of this aircraft began in 1988 as a competitor to the 747, the A380 made its first test flight in April 2005.
[src:eric-reissner/aerospace-engineering] The basis of most of these elements lies in theoretical physics, such as fluid dynamics for aerodynamics or the equations of motion for flight dynamics.
[src:eric-reissner/aerospace-engineering] There is also a large empirical component.
[src:eric-reissner/aerospace-engineering] Historically, this empirical component was derived from testing of scale models and prototypes, either in wind tunnels or in the free atmosphere.
[src:eric-reissner/aerospace-engineering] More recently, advances in computing have enabled the use of computational fluid dynamics to simulate the behavior of the fluid, reducing time and expense spent on wind-tunnel testing.
[src:eric-reissner/aerospace-engineering] Those studying hydrodynamics or hydroacoustics often obtain degrees in aerospace engineering.
[src:eric-reissner/aerospace-engineering] Aerospace engineering may be studied at the advanced diploma, bachelor's, master's, and Ph.D. levels in aerospace engineering departments at many universities, and in mechanical engineering departments at others.
[src:eric-reissner/aerospace-engineering] A few departments offer degrees in space-focused astronautical engineering.
[src:eric-reissner/aerospace-engineering] Some institutions differentiate between aeronautical and astronautical engineering.
[src:eric-reissner/aerospace-engineering] Graduate degrees are offered in advanced or specialty areas for the aerospace industry.
[src:eric-reissner/aerospace-engineering] A background in chemistry, physics, computer science and mathematics is important for students pursuing an aerospace engineering degree.
[src:eric-reissner/aerospace-engineering] The term "rocket scientist" is sometimes used to describe a person of great intelligence since rocket science is seen as a practice requiring great mental ability, especially technically and mathematically.
[src:eric-reissner/aerospace-engineering] The term is used ironically in the expression "It's not rocket science" to indicate that a task is simple.
[src:eric-reissner/aerospace-engineering] Strictly speaking, the use of "science" in "rocket science" is a misnomer since science is about understanding the origins, nature, and behavior of the universe; engineering is about using scientific and engineering principles to solve problems and develop new technology.
[src:eric-reissner/aerospace-engineering] The more etymologically correct version of this phrase would be "rocket engineer".
[src:eric-reissner/aerospace-engineering] However, "science" and "engineering" are often misused as synonyms.
[src:eric-reissner/alan-howard-engineer] Howard was born in Washington, D.C., in 1905.
[src:eric-reissner/alan-howard-engineer] He obtained his BSc in electrical engineering from Purdue University in 1927.
[src:eric-reissner/alan-howard-engineer] After his graduation in 1927, Howard started his lifelong career at the General Electric Company in Schenectady, New York as electrical engineer.
[src:eric-reissner/alan-howard-engineer] He advanced rapidly various positions, and moved into steam turbine activities in 1941.
[src:eric-reissner/alan-howard-engineer] In World War II at General Electric, Howard managed the development of aircraft gas turbine engine for the United States Air Force, and developed the TG 100 and TG 180 turboprop engine.
[src:eric-reissner/alan-howard-engineer] Coffin Award by General Electric for his "accomplishments in connection with the design and development of the TG100 and TG180 aircraft gas turbines." In 1954, he was awarded the honorary degree of doctor of engineering by Purdue University.
[src:eric-reissner/alan-howard-engineer] In 1962, he had been elected Fellow of the American Society of Mechanical Engineers, and in 1964, he was awarded the ASME Medal.
[src:eric-reissner/albert-kingsbury] Albert Kingsbury was born in Morris, Illinois and graduated from Cuyahoga Falls High School, OH in 1880.
[src:eric-reissner/albert-kingsbury] In addition to his interest in tribology and bearings, Kingsbury enjoyed the world of arts, history, and letters.
[src:eric-reissner/albert-kingsbury] He devoted much time to the study of foreign languages.
[src:eric-reissner/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury died in Greenwich, Connecticut 1943, and is buried at the Green-Wood Cemetery, Brooklyn, New York.
[src:eric-reissner/albert-kingsbury] In 1884, Kingsbury attended the University of Akron to study Scientific-Latin courses.
[src:eric-reissner/albert-kingsbury] He dropped out and worked as a machine apprentice in Cuyahoga Falls.
[src:eric-reissner/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury credited this as an important experience that led him to advance his career in engineering.
[src:eric-reissner/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury resumed his formal education at Ohio State University, but he again dropped out to work as a machinist with the Warner and Swasey Company in Cleveland.
[src:eric-reissner/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury received his mechanical engineering degree from Cornell University in 1887.
[src:eric-reissner/albert-kingsbury] It was at Cornell that he met Professor Robert Henry Thurston.
[src:eric-reissner/albert-kingsbury] Professor Thurston was instrumental in shaping Kingsbury's interest in bearings and tribology.
[src:eric-reissner/albert-kingsbury] Working under Professor Thurston, Kingsbury conducted tests on bearing materials for the Pennsylvania Railroad.
[src:eric-reissner/albert-kingsbury] His craftsmanship, honed by his experience in machine shops, allowed Kingsbury to fit half-bushings to the journal by scraping.
[src:eric-reissner/albert-kingsbury] His hand fitting produced the small tolerances that promoted film lubrication.
[src:eric-reissner/albert-kingsbury] These bearings, when ran showed no measurable signs of wear, and was Kingsbury's prompt to the creation of the thrust bearings which now bear his name.
[src:eric-reissner/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury pursued a teaching position at the University of New Hampshire.
[src:eric-reissner/albert-kingsbury] Within two years, he was a professor of Mechanical Engineering courses at the university.
[src:eric-reissner/albert-kingsbury] His new position at the university allowed him to continue pursuing his interest in lubrication.
[src:eric-reissner/albert-kingsbury] During his time at the University of New Hampshire, he created an innovative test machine to measure friction in coarse pitch, lubricated screw threads at loads of up to 14,000 psi.
[src:eric-reissner/albert-kingsbury] The usefulness of this invention received mixed reviews from the American Society of Mechanical Engineers (ASME).
[src:eric-reissner/albert-kingsbury] His research also covered fluid lubricated bearings, and he published a paper entitled "Experiments with an Air Lubricated Bearing".
[src:eric-reissner/albert-kingsbury] It was at this university that he envisioned the Kingsbury thrust bearing.
[src:eric-reissner/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury joined the Worcester Polytechnic Institute to continue pursuing his interest in lubrication.
[src:eric-reissner/albert-kingsbury] He secured expansions for laboratory facilities and funding to continue his tests on a centrally pivoted thrust bearing with the aid of his students.
[src:eric-reissner/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury's research at the University of New Hampshire led him to conceive an early Kingsbury bearing that consisted of several stationary arc segments facing a thrust collar on the rotating shaft.
[src:eric-reissner/albert-kingsbury] Each segment would have a boss on the side away from the thrust collar, allowing it to tilt and form an oil wedge that would carry the thrust.
[src:eric-reissner/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury tested this new bearing with a modified version of his earlier screw thread testing machine.
[src:eric-reissner/albert-kingsbury] The bearing was successful with pressures of up to 4,000 psi at speeds of 285 rpm.
[src:eric-reissner/albert-kingsbury] This pressure exceeded that for common collar-type bearings by a factor of 80 to 100, thus proving the promise of the Kingsbury bearing.
[src:eric-reissner/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury joined the Westinghouse Electric Company in Pittsburgh as a general engineer.
[src:eric-reissner/albert-kingsbury] He used this as an opportunity to advance the development of his thrust bearings in an industrial setting.
[src:eric-reissner/albert-kingsbury] Unfortunately, the first test of his thrust bearing was a failure.
[src:eric-reissner/albert-kingsbury] His bearing overheated during the test and was discarded.
[src:eric-reissner/albert-kingsbury] This made the company skeptical of Kingsbury's invention, but Westinghouse's skepticism did not dent Kingsbury's enthusiasm.
[src:eric-reissner/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury would later fund his own test that proved his bearings successful.
[src:eric-reissner/albert-kingsbury] Unfortunately, Westinghouse decided to stick to more conventional ball bearings for their motors.
[src:eric-reissner/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury tried to file for a U.S. patent during 1907.
[src:eric-reissner/albert-kingsbury] His initial application was rejected as a British patent had been granted in 1905 to A.G.M.
[src:eric-reissner/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury was able to demonstrate that his 1898 test at the University of New Hampshire predated Michell's work, so in 1910 Kingsbury was awarded US patent No.
[src:eric-reissner/albert-kingsbury] 947242 for the tilting pad thrust bearing.
[src:eric-reissner/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury would eventually run his own business with the Westinghouse Machine Co. building his bearings.
[src:eric-reissner/albert-kingsbury] This allowed him to actively pursue applications for his newly patented thrust bearing.
[src:eric-reissner/albert-kingsbury] His first chance came when the Pennsylvania Water and Power Co. gave him the opportunity to demonstrate his bearing on their power generator at the Susquehanna River.
[src:eric-reissner/albert-kingsbury] His first bearing was a failure as it was immediately destroyed by Hillson wiping.
[src:eric-reissner/albert-kingsbury] Fortunately for Kingsbury, the Pennsylvania Water and Power Co. gave him a second chance.
[src:eric-reissner/albert-kingsbury] His bearing succeeded this time, and worked flawlessly for the next 25 years.
[src:eric-reissner/albert-kingsbury] When it was inspected after 25 years, there was so little evidence of wear that it was calculated that the bearing would last 1,300 to 1,700 years.
[src:eric-reissner/albert-kingsbury] The same bearing is still operating smoothly today.
[src:eric-reissner/albert-kingsbury] In 1921, the Kingsbury thrust bearing had become so popular that Westinghouse could no longer keep up with the demand, thus prompting Kingsbury to set up his own manufacturing plant.
[src:eric-reissner/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury continued to pursue his interest in bearings and tribology later in his life.
[src:eric-reissner/albert-kingsbury] One of his greatest achievements was his analysis of the effects of side leakage of lubricants from bearings.
[src:eric-reissner/albert-kingsbury] By recognizing the analogy in the equations for lubrication and those for electrical flow in a conductive fluid and variable depth, Kingsbury was able to make complicated predictions of slider load capacity well before the advent of computers.
[src:eric-reissner/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury made important contributions to the area of boundary lubrication.
[src:eric-reissner/albert-kingsbury] He was the first to recognize that some fluid lubricants possess a friction-reducing property that is independent of viscosity, which he called 'oiliness'.
[src:eric-reissner/albert-kingsbury] His findings were of great significance since they demonstrated that the hydrodynamic theory of lubrication did not describe completely the lubricating mechanism of fluids.
[src:eric-reissner/albert-kingsbury] Later work by Hardy and Doubleday showed that this property was related to the ability of polar lubricants to adsorb and form close-packed monolayers on the sliding surfaces.
[src:eric-reissner/albert-kingsbury] for his wide-ranging contributions to the field, Kingsbury was named as one of the 23 "Men of Tribology" by Duncan Dowson.
[src:eric-reissner/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury received many accolades for his contributions to science and engineering.
[src:eric-reissner/albert-kingsbury] He was awarded the Gold Medal of the American Society of Mechanical Engineers in 1931; the Elliott Cresson Medal of the Franklin Institute; and honorary doctorates from the University of New Hampshire and Worcester Polytechnic Institute.
[src:eric-reissner/albert-kingsbury] He was elected Honorary Member of ASME in 1940.
[src:eric-reissner/albert-kingsbury] The Kingsbury Hall at the University of New Hampshire also pays homage to the great inventor.
[src:eric-reissner/albert-kingsbury] Albert Kingsbury was inducted into the National Inventors Hall of Fame.
[src:eric-reissner/ambrose-swasey] Swasey was born near Exeter, New Hampshire to Nathaniel and Abigail Swasey.
[src:eric-reissner/ambrose-swasey] He apprenticed as a machinist at the Exeter Machine Works and was afterwards employed at Pratt & Whitney.
[src:eric-reissner/ambrose-swasey] As his career progressed, he became a foreman in the gear-cutting section.
[src:eric-reissner/ambrose-swasey] He developed a new technique for making gear-tooth cutters.
[src:eric-reissner/ambrose-swasey] In 1880, he and Warner formed their eponymous firm, which quickly moved to Cleveland, Ohio.
[src:eric-reissner/ambrose-swasey] Swasey would perform the engineering and machine development at this company.
[src:eric-reissner/ambrose-swasey] The close friends Warner and Swasey built their homes next to each other on Euclid Avenue in Cleveland, a street that was known as "Millionaire's Row".
[src:eric-reissner/ambrose-swasey] In addition to army ordnance contracts, the firm of Warner & Swasey became notable for their work on astronomical observatories and equipment.
[src:eric-reissner/ambrose-swasey] The founders were interested in astronomy as an avocation, and in the field's quest for better optical telescopes, which was burgeoning at the time.
[src:eric-reissner/ambrose-swasey] They also realized that obtaining contracts to build large astronomical observatories would provide publicity for their company.
[src:eric-reissner/ambrose-swasey] In 1885, Swasey completed work at McCormick Observatory on the 45-foot dome, which was the largest in the world, and had a unique, 3 shutter design.
[src:eric-reissner/ambrose-swasey] In 1887, Swasey built the mount for the 36-inch refracting telescope at Lick Observatory.
[src:eric-reissner/ambrose-swasey] In 1898, he manufactured a dividing engine for the U.S.
[src:eric-reissner/ambrose-swasey] Naval Observatory that was used to make the meridian circles.
[src:eric-reissner/ambrose-swasey] Both the building and dome of the Dominion Astrophysical Observatory were made by Warner and Swasey Co.
[src:eric-reissner/ambrose-swasey] Other observatory telescopes and components were built by the company at the Kenwood Observatory, Yerkes Observatory, Argentine National Observatory, the Swasey Observatory at Denison University, and the Case School of Applied Science Observatory.
[src:eric-reissner/ambrose-swasey] From 1904 until 1905, he was the president of the American Society of Mechanical Engineers.
[src:eric-reissner/ambrose-swasey] Both Warner and Swasey were amateur astronomers.
[src:eric-reissner/ambrose-swasey] When they became trustees of the Case School of Applied Science, they donated to the school their private observatory, which they had built between their neighboring houses in East Cleveland.
[src:eric-reissner/ambrose-swasey] Relocated to a new building, this became the Warner and Swasey Observatory.
[src:eric-reissner/ambrose-swasey] The observatory maintained by the department today is still known by this name today.
[src:eric-reissner/ambrose-swasey] Swasey Hall (1917, "懷士堂"), a red brick hall, is the landmark of Sun Yat-sen University, one of the top colleges in China.
[src:eric-reissner/ambrose-swasey] It was named after Swasey for his USD$25000 donation to the then university Christian YMCA society hall.
[src:eric-reissner/ambrose-swasey] The chimes in the chapel were included as a memorial to his wife, Lavinia Marston Swasey.
[src:eric-reissner/ambrose-swasey] The Warner & Swasey Company he cofounded would continue until 1980, when it was acquired by Bendix Corporation.
[src:eric-reissner/asme-medal] The **ASME Medal**, created in 1920, is the highest award bestowed by the ASME (founded as the American Society of Mechanical Engineers) Board of Governors for "eminently distinguished engineering achievement".
[src:eric-reissner/asme-medal] The award has been presented every year since 1996 (first medalist was awarded in 1921), and it consists of a $15,000 honorarium, a certificate, a travel supplement not to exceed $750, and a gold medal inscribed with the words, "What is not yet, may be".
[src:eric-reissner/asme-medal] ASME also gives out a number of other awards yearly, including the Edwin F.
[src:eric-reissner/asme-medal] Church Medal, the Holley medal, and the Soichiro Honda medal.
[src:eric-reissner/eric-reissner] Reissner is known as co-developer of the Mindlin–Reissner plate theory.
[src:eric-reissner/eric-reissner] Reissner was born in Aachen, Germany, son of Hans Jacob Reissner, an aeronautical engineer, and Josefine (Reichenberger) Reissner.
[src:eric-reissner/eric-reissner] At the Technische Hochschule Berlin-Charlottenburg he obtained dregrees in Applied Mathematics in 1935, and in Civil Engineering in 1936.
[src:eric-reissner/eric-reissner] Reissner started his academic career in 1938 at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology, where he taught mathematics.
[src:eric-reissner/eric-reissner] In 1947 he was appointed Professor of Mathematics, and served in this position until 1969.
[src:eric-reissner/eric-reissner] Next from 1969 to 1979 he was Professor of Applied Mechanics and Engineering Sciences at the University of California, San Diego.
[src:eric-reissner/eric-reissner] From 1948 to 1955 he had also been researcher at NASA's Langley Research Center, and from 1956 to 1957 at Lockheed's Palo Alto Research Center.
[src:eric-reissner/eric-reissner] Reissner was awarded a Guggenheim Fellowship in 1962.
[src:eric-reissner/eric-reissner] He was awarded the honorary doctor by the University of Hanover, and was elected honorary member by the Society for Applied Mathematics and Mechanics (GAMM).
[src:eric-reissner/eric-reissner] He received the Timoshenko Medal in 1973, the Theodore von Karman Medal in 1964, and of the ASME Medal in 1988.
